<TEXT>
three intellectuals who have been the governments 
only vocal critics since the student movement for democracy was 
suppressed last year disappeared on thursday and their planned news 
conference was canceled 
it was not clear if the three former hunger strikers were 
voluntarily maintaining a low profile or if they were taken into 
custody 
sunday is the anniversary of last years army attack on 
prodemocracy protesters in beijing that left hundreds dead and the 
government has been tightening security measures in anticipation of 
possible disturbances 
also on thursday chinese newspapers reported 20 people were 
executed for crimes including a man convicted of destroying an air 
force jeep during last junes uprising 
the three intellectuals had planned to issue an open letter to 
chinese leaders calling for the release of political prisoners 
friends said two of the three who drafted the letter folk singer 
hou dejian and the former editor of a university newspaper gao xin 
had not been seen since they left hous home early thursday 
several hours later hou telephoned to say he was well but would 
not be coming back for an unspecified time gao 34 telephoned 
later with a similar message 
hou 34 also phoned two foreign journalists and said because 
i personally have things to do im not ready to hold a news 
conference he refused to elaborate 
the third intellectual zhou duo 43 also dropped out of sight 
on thursday 
foreign ministry spokeswoman li jinhua said at the ministrys 
weekly briefing later thursday that chinese were free to talk to 
foreign journalists but a certain kind of formalities should be 
observed for interviews she did not comment directly on the case 
authorities may have been willing to tolerate their criticism 
because it would have only reached a foreign audience and the three 
were so open that they clearly were not involved in any underground 
plotting 
holding a major news conference just days before the anniversary 
may however been too great a provocation most of the foreign 
journalists in beijing were expected to cram hous tiny apartment 
for the meeting 
sundays edition of the official sichuan daily seen in beijing 
on thursday said courts in the capital of sichuan province last 
week sentenced convicted arsonist yu yongchuan to death he was 
immediately executed 
the newspaper said yu led others in overturning a jeep and 
setting it on fire during rioting that broke out in the capital 
chengdu on june 5 the day after the prodemocracy movement was 
crushed 
the other executed people were convicted of a variety of crimes 
</TEXT>
