<TEXT>
if mikhail gorbachev fails to bring home a 
signed trade agreement from his summit meeting with president bush 
it will be another blow to a soviet economy that is already 
reeling analysts say 
both gorbachev and president bush have put major emphasis on a 
new trade agreement as the primary way the united states can 
provide economic support for gorbachevs reform program 
it is a very important trophy for gorbachev it wont solve 
all of his economic problems but not getting a deal will hurt 
said marshall goldman a soviet expert at harvard university 
the pact would normalize trade relations between the two 
superpowers for the first time in nearly a half century and clear 
the way for significantly lower tariffs on soviet products it 
would also expand business opportunites for american companies in 
the soviet union 
donald bowles an economics professor at american university 
said that given the food shortages and other problems besetting the 
soviet economy the boost from a trade agreement should not be 
underestimated 
the more quickly that we can normalize relationships the 
better we can make things for the soviet people generally he 
said that is in our longterm interests 
us and soviet negotiators reached basic agreement on the trade 
pact on april 25 with administration officials expressing optimism 
a month ago that a few minor loose ends could be resolved in time 
for bush and gorbachev to sign the document during this weeks 
summit 
although the administration has not ruled out a signing cremony 
during the fourday summit the outlook has grown considerably less 
certain 
at first the administration said it would not sign a trade 
agreement until the soviet parliament put into law liberalized 
emigration policies for soviet jews and other dissidents 
but now the administration seeking to influence gorbachevs 
handling of the lithuanian independence movement has linked a 
trade agreement with the lifting of moscows economic blockade on 
the breakaway republic 
while bush is being pressured by many members of congress to 
hold firm to this position some us business groups were lobbying 
the administration to go ahead and sign a trade deal 
the national association of manufacturers sent bush a letter 
wednesday saying that the first role of us trade policy was to 
advance americas competitive standing in the world not to serve 
as a poor foreign policy messenger 
without some clear indication that the pending ussoviet 
trade agreement will be implemented american business proposals 
will get short shrift in the soviet union compared with those from 
europe and japan wrote nam president jerry jasinowski 
the trade agreement is needed to grant the soviet union most 
favored nation status qualifying it for the lowest tariffs 
granted to any other country currently soviet products sold in 
the united states bear duties as much as 10 times higher than 
imports from other countries by one estimate the price of soviet 
vodka could drop by 125 per bottle 
us officials have estimated that the 5 billion in annual 
trade between the soviet union and the united states could double 
or even triple over the next three years with a new trade agreement 
in addition to the lower tariffs the agreement includes a 
number of provisions aimed at expanding foreign business 
opportunities the agreement would provide better copyright 
protection for american companies and cut down on the time us 
companies have to wait for approval for commercial operations in 
the soviet union 
the agreement would also clear the way for american companies 
doing business with the soviets to be eligible for 
governmentsubsidized loans from the exportimport bank and the 
overseas private investment corp 
analysts said this provision was significant because it would 
expand the number of us companies interested in setting up joint 
ventures in the soviet union a key goal of gorbachevs economic 
reforms 
the dire economic situation in the soviet union was emphasized 
during a presummit press conference wednesday conducted by a group 
of soviet economists who discussed with unusual candor the slumping 
soviet economy which has been beset by food shortages labor 
strikes and high inflation 
everything we have done so far were half measures one step 
forward and two steps backwards said vladlen martynov director 
of the soviet institute of world economics and international 
relations 
</TEXT>
