<TEXT>
if no superpower trade agreement is 
signed during the washington summit the plight of yuri semenenko 
may be one small reason why 
semenenko holds a us passport by virtue of his birth in 
portland oregon 45 years ago but he still is unable to leave the 
soviet union 
the catch he also holds a soviet passport and visa officials 
say he cannot leave until he gives it up and only they can decide 
if and when he can do that 
semenenko served five years in prison camps on what he said were 
trumpedup criminal charges connected to his effort to obtain a 
us passport in the early 1980s 
for him the political and economic reforms for which the world 
has praised president mikhail s gorbachev are changes in words 
only 
in deeds nothing has changed said semenenko a trim tennis 
fanatic and former motocross racer 
even though he knows portland only through old photographs he 
would like to take his wife yelena a ballet dancer and newborn 
daughter to the city to live 
i have some kind of feeling that the city is my home some 
kind of ties there he said 
travel and emigration from the soviet union have reached record 
levels under gorbachev an israeli immigration agency reported in 
january that 71509 jews left the soviet union in 1989 the highest 
total in about two decades 
but many say gorbachevs reforms have been limited soviet jews 
plan to demonstrate in moscow during the superpower summit to make 
their point 
soviet officials long have promised a new emigration law to 
remove obstacles and president bush has set that as a criterion 
for easing trade restrictions against the soviet union 
under a 1974 us law the soviet union has been denied the 
benefits of most favored nation trading status because of its 
repressive policies toward the emigration of soviet jews and other 
minorities 
bush administration officials have worked on the final wording 
of a trade agreement but it was unclear whether it would be put on 
the table during the summit without a new soviet emigration law 
gorbachevs economic crackdown on lithuania was also hindering an 
accord officials said 
in november the supreme soviet legislature gave preliminary 
approval to a bill that would allow emigration for virtually anyone 
who has entry permission from another country and no outstanding 
alimony obligations criminal charges or recent knowledge of state 
secrets 
it sets a limit of five years on the period a citizen can be 
kept from emigrating because of access to secrets nevertheless 
jewish activists claim the bill is vaguely worded and might still 
be used to restrict emigration 
there are indications the bill might come up for debate soon 
but it has proved little comfort to semenenko and others caught in 
the slow grind of soviet bureaucracy 
semenenko is the son of a soviet military officer assigned to 
oversee lendlease shipments in world war ii and is american by 
virtue of his birth in portlands wilcox memorial hospital on feb 
10 1945 
his family left the united states several months after 
semenenkos birth and he has lived since then in the soviet union 
ten years ago he learned he was eligible for us citizenship 
and in march 1989 obtained a us passport after being released 
from prison camp where he served time on charges of bribery and 
hooliganism 
he began seeking permission from the soviet union to leave but 
was told only the soviet government could decide whether and when 
he can give up his soviet citizenship 
the bureaucracys gears moved another notch in february 
leningrad visa officials invited him to fill out an application to 
give up citizenship and pay a fee of 500 rubles about twice the 
monthly wage for an average factory worker 
but nothing has happened since he paid the fee and filled out 
the form semenenko said calls to the local visa office indicated 
the documents still have not been transmitted to moscow for 
approval 
to semenenko that means my documents are with the kgb and the 
visa office cant do anything about it there is no way to guess 
if the secret police will sign off on his departure he said 
as the soviet union struggles through economic failure ethnic 
tension and political upheaval semenenko said it does not matter 
what kind of life he finds in the united states 
sitting here its impossible to construct any kind of 
possibilities for the future he said im ready for any kind 
of work 
