the navy has grounded its fleet of twinrotor 
h46 sea knight transport helicopters for the second time this 
month 
the 340 helicopters were ordered not to fly after routine 
maintenance found fractures in the rotorhub connecting links that 
hold the rotor blades to their hub said a pentagon statement 
released wednesday 
there are 259 helicopters in the fleet assigned to the marine 
corps and 81 to the navy 
aircraft will be returned to flight status following 
electronic inspections of the connecting links the statement 
said periodic followup inspections will be implemented to 
identify and remove from service any links which show evidence of 
developing cracks 
the problem with the links is not related to trouble in the 
copters aft transmission that led to a may 13 grounding order the 
statement said 
that transmission problem was discovered after an investigation 
of an h46 accident earlier this month 
seventeen marines were injured at the marine airground training 
center at twentynine palms calif when their helicopter made a 
rough landing during an airassault exercise 
the transmission problem meant that the aircrafts rear rotor 
system could lose its drive power 
the helicopters were to be returned to service after the may 13 
grounding and repair 
