<TEXT>
boris n yeltsin newly elected president of the 
russian republic earned his reputation as a radical reformer by 
criticizing the slow pace of reform under mikhail s gorbachev 
following are some of the points on which they differ 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
gorbachev believes the soviet union was right to choose the 
socialist road 72 years ago and that perestroika should merely 
breathe new life into socialism 
yeltsin backed private ownership in his campaign speech and 
never mentioned socialism prompting gorbachev to brand him 
antisocialist 
 
gorbachev refuses to redraw any of the soviet unions internal 
boundaries for fear of unleashing chaos 
yeltsin urges a commission to examine the internal boundaries 
of the russian federation which contains some two dozen autonomous 
regions with an eye to reexamining the boundaries and creating 
new regions 
 
gorbachev has ruled out whittling the soviet army down to a 
small professional corps 
yeltsin says the army must go professional 
 
gorbachev has overseen some reform in the kgb 
yeltsin urges the kgb be merged with the interior ministry in 
one investigative body 
 
gorbachev has been reluctant to take out major foreign loans to 
try to cure the economy 
yeltsin proposes taking out foreign loans and pulling in a 
percent of the governments foreign currency income to gather 20 
billion rubles and direct them mainly toward buying scarce consumer 
products 
 
gorbachev backs government plan to raise prices and introduce a 
fiveyear plan to shift to a partial market economy 
yeltsin says government plan is based on lowering the 
alreadylow soviet standard of living and the shift to a market 
economy can be faster and less painful by changing property laws 
freeing enterprises and taking out foreign loans 
 
gorbachev imposed a partial economic blockade on lithuania 
yeltsin says russia should strike deals with lithuania and 
other regions that want to sign direct contracts with lithuania 
without going through moscow 
 
gorbachev backs the government plan of a maximum tax of 55 
percent on profits 
yeltsin says the maximum should be 35 percent 
