a court today charged a highranking reserve 
officer and a company he heads with illegally providing military 
expertise and equipment to a group of civilians in colombia 
the defendant lt col yair klein is also wanted in that south 
american country for allegedly helping to train fighters for 
cocaine cartels 
the case involving klein and his hod hahanit or spearhead 
company has prompted wide debate in israel over the practice of 
retired military officers working as mercenaries overseas 
kleins company is defined in the charges as an organization 
that trains and builds counterterrorist fighting squads 
the fourpage charge sheet makes no mention of the colombian 
charges that klein was involved in training assassination teams for 
the medellin drug cartel klein has vigorously denied such 
allegations 
a copy of the charge sheet provided to the associated press 
charges klein with making an illegal deal with a group known as the 
farmers organization in colombia around april 1988 
the illegalexport charges by the jerusalem magistrates court do 
not give details on the farmers group klein maintained earlier 
that he had legally provided training to a group of colombian 
cattlemen 
klein who was involved in secret counterterrorist operations 
with the israeli army came under investigation in august 
at the time colombia sought him in connection with a spate of 
drugrelated shootings klein is still wanted in colombia for 
allegedly organizing training and equipping paramilitary groups 
for drug traffickers he has been declared a fugitive from justice 
and may be tried in absentia 
he was also questioned by israeli police last month for an 
alleged role in the illegal diversion of weapons destined for 
antigua to the medellin cartel he has denied any such involvement 
an antiguan commission of inquiry opens hearings on the case 
friday 
