the president of the university of south 
carolina has resigned after weeks of criticism about lavish 
spending on fundraising trips and hiring of celebrities as 
visiting teachers 
james b holderman 54 who has headed the 40000student state 
university since 1977 will step down on july 1 
holderman made no reference to the controversy when he announced 
his resignation wednesday and declined to answer reporters 
questions he read from a statement in front of his home on the 
campus in downtown columbia 
for my whole family this has been more than a job it has 
been a total commitment he said in our collective judgment 
we have determined that it is time to pursue new personal and 
professional challenges 
holderman regularly used luxury hotels while on fundraising 
trips hired 35anhour chauffeured limousine services in 
washington and frequently chartered jets or flew first class 
according to records from the university and private foundations 
affiliated with the school 
holderman argued that expensive hotel rooms were necessary to 
woo wealthy donors and said his critics overlooked the fact that 
he has helped raise 225 million in the past year 
much of the money spent came from the presidents discretionary 
account which is funded not from tax revenue but from such things 
as profits from campus vending machine sales 
as a result of the controversy the board of trustees last week 
implemented guidelines aimed at limiting his expenses forcing him 
to obtain prior approval for exceptional spending and making him 
more accountable for funds spent 
critics said holdermans spending was excessive since during the 
same period he told lawmakers courses were being canceled for lack 
of state funds 
holderman first came under criticism in 1986 for lavish spending 
on his travels for giving expensive gifts to donors and students 
and for paying top dollar to lure celebrity lecturers and speakers 
to the school 
jihan sadat widow of egyptian president anwar sadat was paid 
200000 to teach a course in egyptian culture for three semesters 
in 1985 and 1986 
more recently the school has drawn criticism for paying 
actordirector robby benson 158367 to teach filmmaking and 
15600 for rent with holderman kicking in 10000 from his 
discretionary fund for travel and moving expenses 
board of trustees chairman michael mungo said the board did not 
pressure holderman to resign though he acknowledged that criticism 
of the university because of the spending should end with 
holdermans departure 
