<TEXT>
a chinese couple who fled their homeland 
because of chinas harsh family planning laws have been granted 
political asylum in the united states their lawyer said today 
li jin mu and wang sai zhen are the first known refugees to be 
granted asylum under an order president bush issued last november 
that established fear of forced abortion as grounds for asylum 
at the time they fled china last year ms wang was pregnant 
with the couples second child only one was allowed she had 
undergone several previous abortions and her doctor had warned her 
another could damage her health 
the us immigration and naturalization service notified the 
couple that they had been granted asylum late wednesday said the 
lawyer kathleen rimar she said the letter did not specifically 
mention the abortion issue 
its a form letter rimar said it basically just says 
that they have demonstrated a wellfounded fear of persecution 
ealier this month the state department had recommended that 
asylum be granted 
li 37 and ms wang whose age has not been disclosed now live 
in new york city they must undergo a followup interview with the 
ins within a year to confirm their asylum status rimar said 
after the asylum is confirmed the couple would qualify for 
permanent resident status although it could be a few years before 
they win it because of a backlog of applications rimar said five 
years after becoming permanent residents they could qualify for 
citizenship 
the couple fled their hometown of fuzhou early last year along 
with a nephew chun kong cheung 19 and made their way to canada 
there they paid smugglers about 1500 apiece to get them into the 
united states 
the ins caught them in albany and sent li and chun back to 
canada ms wang was allowed to stay because of her advanced 
pregnancy and gave birth to a daughter in new york li and chun 
tried again to get into the united states last october but 
government agents found them in the back of a truck at a border 
crossing near buffalo 
the three applied for asylum after bush issued his nov 30 
order which was part of a directive allowing chinese students to 
stay in the united states after the tiananmen square massacre of 
prodemocracy demonstrators in beijing 
the couple left their first child a 10yearold daughter 
behind with relatives in china they have said they would like to 
go back someday and get her 
the state department has rejected the nephews application for 
asylum but rimar said she has asked it to reconsider he is still 
in the united states but the ins is trying to have him sent back 
to canada 
