at least five toxic chemicals from the 
rocky mountain arsenal including a nerve gas byproduct and two 
banned pesticides have migrated underground four miles to the 
south platte river officials said 
environmental protection agency officials said wednesday that 
they did not believe there was any public health threat from the 
wastes dumped by the army and shell oil co 
when it reaches the south platte its very diluted said 
connally mears who directs an epasupervised cleanup at the 
arsenal north of stapleton international airport 
the epa had not previously disclosed that pollution from the 
arsenal was affecting the south platte which supplies water for 
drinking and irrigation to thousands of rural northeastern colorado 
residents 
the pollution apparently is seeping around the edges of 
underground barrier systems the army and shell built along the 
arsenals northern and northwestern borders to cleanse groundwater 
the 27squaremile arsenals contamination of groundwater dates 
to the early 1950s shell oil co manufactured pesticides at the 
arsenal for 30 years beginning in 1952 before that the army 
manufactured and stored chemical warfare weapons there 
epa officials said a plume consisting of many pollutants reached 
the river but they are chiefly concerned about five an army nerve 
gas byproduct called dimp pce an industrial solvent chloroform 
dieldrin a shell pesticide banned for most uses in 1974 because of 
links to cancer and dbcp a shell pesticide banned for most uses 
in 1979 because it can cause sterility in workers 
the key uncertainty is over the longterm health effects of 
dimp mears said 
