east german lawmakers voted today to create a 
commission that will investigate and perhaps seize the vast 
property held by the former communist party 
the coalition government of prime minister lothar de maiziere 
asked parliament to form a commission that would have broad powers 
to seize evidence search houses and interrogate witnesses 
when it is created in the next few days all property owned by 
political parties and other organizations under the former regime 
would be put in trust while the government decides how to dispose 
of it 
the law was passed as the young democratic government grapples 
with how to convert stateowned property to private ownership a 
prerequisite to unification with west germany 
the two german states are to merge their economies and social 
institutions on july 2 when west german currency will become the 
currency of east germany 
the property commission is to report its findings to parliament 
by june 30 
the commission is part of the monumental process of dismantling 
the nations vast system of state ownership 
the proposal calls for the property of all political parties 
unions and other organizations to be investigated but it is 
clearly aimed at the former communist regime 
lawmaker gregor gysi leader of the reconstituted communist 
party that now supports a form of democratic socialism said the 
government proposal was aimed at eliminating his partys role as an 
opposition faction 
they want all opposition eliminated said gysi whose party 
is now called the party of democratic socialism that is the goal 
and nothing else he said his party already has given up a large 
part of its property 
richard schroeder leader of the social democratic lawmakers in 
parliament said the proposal is aimed at merely shedding light on 
who owns what in the country 
we should bring clarity and light to the property 
proportion he said we have the impression that the history of 
the former communist party property is still being written 
the leftleaning social democrats are part of conservative de 
maizieres coalition 
under the governments proposal the property commission would 
report back to the parliament by june 30 
the issue of distributing east german property has generated 
much argument in both germanys 
hans klein spokesman for west german chancellor helmut kohl 
said on wednesday that property seized when the communists assumed 
control of east germany 40 years ago should be given back to the 
original owners 
more than 1 million west germans are expected to lay claim to 
property they or their ancestors left behind when fleeing after 
world war ii or during the communist regime 
east germany wants instead to pay compensation to former owners 
and let east germans have the initial opportunity to buy the 
property 
some west germans already have written letters to tenants of 
east german apartments warning them that they will seek to claim 
the land on which the buildings stand 
east germans also fear high unemployment and rising prices when 
the two nations merge their economies 
east germans have been lining up at grocery stores to stock up 
on food and other household goods creating huge shortages of meat 
milk and other basic necessities officials said 
lawmaker vera wollenberger said meat was selling out in stores 
within one hour of opening in the cities of east berlin and halle 
commerce minister sybille reider said consumer demand has 
increased 300 percent to 400 percent in recent days soap bread 
and other goods are selling out she said 
