<TEXT>
orders to us factories slumped 23 percent in 
april helping to push orders for the year so far down 2 percent 
the government said thursday in a report showing further evidence of 
a slow manufacturing economy 
basically it shows the manufacturing sector is still dead in 
the water said evelina tainer senior domestic economist with the 
first national bank of chicago its just not going anywhere 
the commerce department said orders to factories for both durable 
and nondurable manufactured goods totaled a seasonally adjusted 
2356 billion that followed gains of 4 percent in march and 18 
percent in february 
despite the gains the april decline and a 55 percent drop in 
january means factory orders have fallen 2 percent in the years 
first four months and the department said orders have been 
relatively flat since the beginning of 1989 
the january decline was the steepest since a 7 percent plunge in 
december 1974 
factory orders are a key economic barometer of manufacturing 
industry plans for production a decrease in orders may forecast a 
slump in that sector and layoffs in the future 
the decrease in april new orders was concentrated in the 
durable goods sector which declined 43 percent to 1234 
billion the department said revising the drop in durable orders 
from the 41 percent decline first reported last week 
the largest decrease was in transportation equipment down 
147 percent to 317 billion it added both motor vehicles and 
aircraft were down excluding transportation orders were 
unchanged 
transportation orders had risen 241 percent in march and 101 
percent in february 
also unchanged during april were nondurable orders which 
remained at 1122 billion 
in the key category of nondefense capital goods a barometer of 
business investment plans orders fell 98 percent to 369 billion 
after a 133 percent gain the previous month excluding aircraft 
they were off 02 percent in april and 11 percent in march 
michael k evans of evans economics inc a washington 
forecasting firm said the capital goods spending report spells bad 
news for industrial production 
businesses are starting to pull in their horns evans said 
because of high interest rates and a 16 percent decline in profits 
last year and in the first quarter theyre not getting any 
better 
the volatile defense category posted a 2 percent gain to 8 
billion after advances of 45 percent in march and 183 percent in 
february excluding defense orders fell 24 percent 
inventories ticked up 01 percent to 3723 billion following two 
months of declines but ms tainer said they remain lean 
if inventories were to increase without a corresponding gain in 
orders production cutbacks could occur as factories try to get rid 
of goods stored on shelves and backlots often causing job layoffs 
besides transportation orders other durable declines included 
orders for nonelectrical machinery down 29 percent to 217 
billion and primary metals down 14 percent to 116 billion 
electrical machinery orders rose 4 percent to 204 billion after 
falling 17 percent in march and rising 28 percent in february 
