<TEXT>
lawmakers on thursday repealed a 
40yearold law giving east german resettlers special benefits and 
they tightened rules on ethnic germans emigrating from elsewhere in 
eastern europe 
the decision to repeal the law on resettlers is expected to gain 
automatic approval of the bundesrat or upper house of parliament 
the effective date for repealing the law is july 1 one day 
before monetary social and economic union of the two germanys is to 
take effect 
the law provided special benefits including housing and 
financial assistance for east german resettlers to west germany and 
granted them automatic west german citizenship 
repealing the law means that east germans will be treated exactly 
like west germans who decide to move to other parts of the country 
more than 500000 east germans have resettled in west germany 
since january 1989 
the influx last fall brought on the downfall of the hardline 
east german communist government and led to the countrys first free 
elections in march 
but east germans continued to flood into west germany straining 
west germanys already tight housing and social services 
chancellor helmut kohls government resisted cutting the 
resettlers benefits until the monetary union takes effect 
in addition to the east germans some 175000 ethnic germans from 
other east european countries have arrived in west germany this year 
the legislators thursday tightened requirements for ethnic 
germans emirgating from east europe they must now apply at west 
german embassies to be recognized as ethnic germans in their 
homelands before they are granted permission to immigrate to west 
germany 
in the past the emigres could arrive in west germany and then 
apply to be recognized as ethnic germans 
</TEXT>
