<TEXT>
san francisco officials dont want to wait 
until the next big earthquake to repair and protect about two dozen 
municipal buildings including city hall from the ravages of a 
major tremor 
so nearly eight months after the oct 17 quake voters are being 
asked tuesday to approve the citys largestever bond measure to pay 
for quake repairs and quakeproofing 
mayor art agnos and other city leaders are pushing proposition a 
which would allow the city to raise 332 million to pay for quake 
repairs and seismic improvements to the cityowned buildings during 
the next decade 
you cannot escape the reality that this work has to be done 
said rudy nothenberg the citys chief administrative officer 
there has been little controversy surrounding proposition a he 
said the measure has been unanimously endorsed by the city board of 
supervisors and faces no opposition from other groups 
this is work the city would have had to do in any event sooner 
or later and given our experience in the last year we thought 
sooner rather than later said nothenberg 
the biggest chunk of the money 207 million would be spent 
preparing about 20 buildings including city hall and the war 
memorial opera house for another quake 
the second priority would be addressing the estimated 53 million 
in needed earthquakedamage repairs left over from the october quake 
an additional 26 million would be spent to fix underground sewer 
lines and pipes at the san francisco zoo that fractured in the quake 
the federal government may eventually reimburse the city for an 
undetermined amount of the repair costs nothenberg said 
the quake which measured 71 on the richter scale caused more 
than 7 billion in damage in northern california 
a month after the earthquake voters approved an 60 million bond 
issue for emergency repairs and some initial seismic strengthening 
most of the buildings on the proposition a list are in critical 
need of strengthening or repairs because of the numbers of people 
that use them 
city hall requires the most timeconsuming and expensive work 
it will cost about 94 million to make the building more quake 
resistant through a method called base isolation nothenberg 
said 
city hall would be separated from its foundation and placed on 
rollers that would absorb some of the shock when the next quake 
hits he said an additional 23 million would be spent to fix a 
crack in the plaster of the rotunda and reattach loose marble on 
walls and archways 
the bond issue also would pay for less expensive repairs and 
reinforcements to the 3000seat opera house the 10000seat civic 
auditorium the veterans building and the public health building 
