immediately announced he would seek sovereignty for russia giving 
its laws precedence over national law and effectively weakening the 
union over which gorbachev presides 
the white house in recent months has expressed a desire to 
buttress gorbachev at home after concluding that soviet stability 
and gorbachevs political survival are in the us interest 
overriding anxiety over issues such as lithuania 
agreement on a new trade pact which would provide some tangible 
benefits for the soviets is essentially at hand but bush has 
backed away from signing it he initially cited the soviet 
parliaments postponement of passage of a new law liberalizing 
emigration policies now the administration is linking agreement on 
trade with the lifting of moscows economic blockade against the 
tiny baltic republic 
even with a trade agreement the soviets would enjoy few 
immediate benefits because their industries do not now produce much 
that could compete on world markets improving production through 
better training quality control and industrial design will take 
years in an economy that has effectively destroyed the work ethic 
and has yet to implement longpromised market incentives 
the soviet president has argued passionately for trade 
concessions to help his country pull out of its economic tailspin 
but few suggest there is anything short of a massive airlift that 
could work fast enough to have an impact on the problems feeding 
present public anxieties 
gorbachevs other summit goals agreement on cutting nuclear 
weapons by 50 percent eliminating chemical weapons and establishing 
a nonthreatening military posture for a unified germany are 
unlikely to help him much at home where he already has established 
his credentials as a peacemaker but returning empty handed could 
further weaken his stature if he were viewed as losing his 
effectiveness in the international arena 
at their first summit meeting in malta last december gorbachev 
and bush announced they would try to reach broad agreement on 
reducing troops and conventional weapons in europe by their next 
meeting 
that goal has proved elusive and us officials say the soviets 
are stalling and attribute the lack of progress to soviet concern 
about the future of germany other observers have suggested 
gorbachev may want to slow the pace of withdrawal from europe not 
just for security reasons but because he is under pressure from his 
own military which has no place to house homecoming troops and 
little enthusiasm for mustering out large numbers of career officers 
in the shrinking of defense forces 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
michael putzel is the associated press moscow 
bureau chief 
</TEXT>
