<TEXT>
police have begun evicting the citys panhandlers 
and homeless from their last great public refuges the subways 
pennsylvania station and grand central terminal 
the transit authority on wednesday began aggressively ejecting 
panhandlers from the subways and removing sleeping people from 
station floors and benches 
the metronorth commuter railroad and the long island rail road 
said that on friday they will begin enforcing courtapproved 
regulations banning begging and various activities such as sleeping 
or using more than one bench seat primarily associated with the 
homeless 
the evictions have drawn criticism from advocates for the 
homeless 
in recent years the homeless have gone to grand central penn 
station and the subways in search of warmth during the winter and 
for safety yearround 
on may 10 the 2nd us circuit court of appeals ruled that 
panhandling in transit systems didnt amount to constitutionally 
protected free speech 
the courts clearly said the subways are not the place to wage 
the social battles transit authority police chief william j 
bratton said thursday they have to be waged elsewhere 
bratton said authorities have to demonstrate that they are in 
control of the subways its been quite apparent that the previous 
approach to panhandling was not giving that sense at all that we 
were being laughed at he said 
an estimated 400 people a night have been spending the night at 
penn station officials said a count for grand central wasnt 
immediately available 
the prohibition on panhandling was part of operation enforcement 
a set of rules outlined by the transit authority last october 
in april the metropolitan transit authority which overesees the 
transit authority and the commuter railroads approved regulations 
for behavior in railroad stations 
under brattons orders beggars are to be ejected without warning 
regardless of whether they are aggressive or passive the police 
chief said he would be satisfied with a 25 percent reduction in 
panhandling 
he also labeled as bogus and baloney accusations that the 
effort against begging would divert officers from fighting 
escalating crime in the subways 
among those criticizing the evictions was peter smith of the 
partnership for the homeless advocacy group 
where are the homeless supposed to go where are they supposed 
to beg smith said is the mta going to put together a shuttle 
to the moon its getting absurd 
but the eviction plan is supported by shopkeepers at penn station 
its not good for business to have people sleeping down here 
said singh cheema who runs a jewelry store near track 17 some 
customers are offended 
at 2 am on any given night at penn station the homeless sleep 
side by side pregnant women children grayhaired men with 
crutches by their sides an occasional person with a dirty plaster 
cast on an arm the huddled line stretches for a block 
until friday the sleepers were rousted at 5 am on friday 
anyone lying down at any time or using more than one bench seat will 
be awakened and told about available social services said long 
island rail road spokesman brian dolan 
if they refuse to take advantage of the assistance offered 
they will be told to leave the station dolan said they will be 
ejected 
at grand central metro north has already closed off many areas 
previously inhabited by the homeless and began enforcing the 
panhandling ban the day after the may 10 court ruling social 
services are available there also 
