<TEXT>
the legislature of soviet moldavia on thursday 
recognized lithuanias independence the tass news agency reported 
making it the first soviet republic outside the baltics to do so 
the move by lawmakers in the southwestern republic represented a 
direct challenge to soviet president mikhail s gorbachevs efforts 
to isolate lithuania from the rest of the soviet union 
gorbachev imposed an economic embargo of key raw materials to the 
baltic republic for failure to rescind its proindependence laws 
and he has decreed lithuanias march 11 declaration of independence 
to be unconstitutional 
according to the official news agency tass deputies of the 
moldavian supreme soviet meeting in the capital of kishinev 
favored the establishment of direct diplomatic economic political 
and cultural relations with lithuania 
the legislature also proposed to exchange permanent missions 
with the lithuanian parliament or supreme council tass reported 
the news agency did not give vote totals on the measure 
so far only the baltic republics of latvia and estonia have 
formally acted to cooperate on such levels with lithuania on may 
12 the three baltic republics revived a 1934 political alliance 
pledging mutual cooperation 
tass noted promoscow deputies who are members of the soviet 
moldavia alliance opposed the decision on recognition 
specifically objecting to the term diplomatic ties they said 
that term cannot be applied between republics that are part of the 
same nation tass said 
the news agency added that some members of the group were not 
represented at the session because deputies from predominantly 
russianspeaking towns have not attended parliament since may 22 it 
gave no reason for their absence 
like the baltic states the region that is now moldavia was 
forcibly annexed into the soviet union by josef stalin in 1940 
before the annexation moldavia then called bessarabia was part 
of romania and had long been regarded as a cradle of romanian 
culture 
the moldavian peoples front an independent political movement 
has been pressing demands for greater autonomy from moscow although 
it has moved cautiously on any reunification with romania 
the peoples front won a battle to establish moldavian as the 
official language of the republic and return to the latin alphabet 
used by romanians dropping the cyrillic letters of the russian 
alphabet imposed under stalin 
gorbachevs embargo imposed april 18 cut off all oil most 
supplies of natural gas and other key raw materials to lithuania 
after it failed to rescind proindependence laws 
since then lithuanian officials have sought to establish ties 
with other soviet republics to trade for materials the republic 
desperately needs one major obstacle to such an arrangement 
however is that moscow controls rail lines and highways needed to 
transport goods to lithuania 
</TEXT>
