<TEXT>
a defunct petroleum disposal company was 
charged thursday with illegally burning dumping and storing 
hazardous waste including surplus napalm bombs 
prosecutors alleged that a puddle of waste from the company was 
so noxious it melted the shoe soles of a passing jogger 
an environmental crime is like a robbery or assault against all 
of us said attorney general richard thornburgh who came to town 
to announce the first federal felony environmental prosecution in 
utah 
a 12count indictment alleges steven f self of fallbrook 
calif and his defunct ekotek inc of knowingly ignoring federal 
environmental laws 
the indictment provides a clear signal to environmental 
profiteers seeking to improperly cash in on the growing 
wastehandling business thornburgh said 
the indictment alleges ekotek duped environmentally conscious 
businesses into believing that waste materials were being properly 
disposed of 
the indictment alleges conspiracy to violate the clean air water 
and resources conservation and recovery acts and involves charges 
that self and others illegally burned and discharged solvents oils 
grease and contaminated runoff then concealed the violations by 
falsifying manifests and logs 
selfs attorney in salt lake city didnt respond to telephone 
requests for comment 
before ekotek was shut down by state regulators in october 1987 
residents of nearby homes complained of malodorous smoke coming from 
the site 
prosecutors said a 17yearold boy reported his shoe began to 
bubble and disintegrate after he accidentally stepped in a 
puddle while running by the site 
ekotek which was in the business of recycling or destroying 
waste oil products discharged into the public sewer system 
approximately 10000 gallons of wastewater per day the indictment 
said 
the indictment alleges that in july 1986 self arranged to accept 
two napalm bombs for testing storage and treatment from the 
navy weapons support center in fallbrook and later told state 
officials they had been properly disposed of state explosives 
experts had to haul the bombs away the following year 
company vice president steven f miller pleaded guilty wednesday 
to three felony charges of conspiracy and violations of federal 
environmental laws 
miller who agreed to testify against self and cooperate with 
cleanup officials in exchange for his plea faces up to 13 years in 
prison and a fine of up to 750000 he remains free on his own 
recognizance 
if convicted on all charges self and the company may be fined up 
to 24 million and self would face a prison term of up to 45 years 
millers california attorney barbara caulfield said her client 
would not comment before his sentencing july 31 
the defendants are alleged to have purchased millions of gallons 
of oils and solvents and burned them as fuel in a refinery which 
was about three miles from downtown salt lake city 
state department of health officials said tens of thousands of 
gallons of wastes have leaked or been dumped into the ground and 
have contaminated nearby homes 
ekotek operated the site from 1981 until october 1987 peter 
stevenson the environmental protection agencys onscene cleanup 
coordinator said agency crews have been stabilizing and evaluating 
the site since 1988 it has designated for epa superfund cleanup 
