<TEXT>
the charred apollo capsule in which 
three astronauts died 23 years ago will remain in storage in 
virginia rather than be buried in an abandoned missile silo or given 
to a museum nasa said thursday 
the capsule was to have been shipped in may from langley research 
center in hampton va to its final resting place in a silo at cape 
canaveral air force station it was to have been buried on top of 
debris from the 1986 challenger explosion americas only other 
space tragedy 
the transfer temporarily was halted after curators at the 
smithsonian institutions national air and space museum said they 
would like to acquire the capsule as an historic artifact the 
kansas cosmosphere and space center in hutchinson kan also had 
expressed interest 
nasa spokesman mark hess said the decision to keep the capsule at 
langley indefinitely was made after conferring with relatives of the 
three astronauts who died and former apollo astronauts 
they just asked us to reconsider and keep it or store it in 
another way hess said 
displaying the capsule at the smithsonian or anywhere else was 
never seriously considered hess said 
i dont think youd find a soul in nasa who thought that was an 
appropriate alternative he said 
mike stephenson associate director of the kansas cosmosphere and 
space center said hes pleased the capsule will not be buried in 
the silo his museum had been interested in the capsule and still 
would be for memorial purposes rather than for display 
its certainly important that the artifact be preserved 
stephenson said 
the capsule has been stored in a locked container at langley 
since the 1967 fire which claimed the lives of astronauts virgil 
gus grissom roger b chaffee and edward h white ii it briefly 
was removed a few weeks ago so its heat shield could be cut into 
pieces for shipping 
the astronauts died when fire engulfed the capsule during a 
countdown rehearsal for the first manned apollo mission the fire 
in a cabin filled with 100 percent oxygen was triggered by a spark 
when a broken or bruised wire beneath grissoms couch contacted 
metal 
thirtyone cartons of hardware and investigative material were 
moved to kennedy space center in late april for burial with the 
capsule they will be returned to langley 
