the justice department said thursday it is 
seeking a court order to enjoin stewart sandwiches inc of norfolk 
va from making and distributing sandwiches until it complies with 
federal health laws 
the complaint filed in us district court in norfolk charges 
that stewart made sandwiches containing potentially lifethreatening 
bacteria 
stewart which claims to be the worlds largest manufacturer of 
sandwiches sold in vending machines and convenience stores is 
accused in the lawsuit of failing to control bacteria contamination 
at its plant in violation of the food drug and cosmetic act 
we will not tolerate any threat to the purity of this nations 
food suypply said stuart m gerson assistant attorney general in 
charge of the civil division 
there was no answer at company headquarters in norfolk 
the department said the food and drug administration received a 
complaint april 12 from florida authorities that bacteria had been 
found in a sandwich made by stewart and sold in that state 
the same day the fda received a complaint from louisiana 
officials that sandwiches shipped to that state were also 
contaminated the department said 
two private test laboratories hired by stewart also found 
bacteriological contamination during an inspection of the companys 
cooked food section in april the department said 
three inspections in 1989 by the fda found unsanitary conditions 
and evidence of bacteria the department said 
the complaint also asks injunctions against stewarts president 
theodore j broecker and donald r beard senior vice president 
