<TEXT>
the united states and the soviet union will 
sign an agreement increasing by nearly fourfold the number of 
commercial flights between us and soviet cities the white house 
announced thursday 
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said the airline 
agreement was one of a series of agreements that would be signed by 
us and soviet officials on friday at the white house 
others include new pacts on ocean studies maritime cooperation 
and cultural exchanges 
the new airline agreement to be signed by secretary of state 
james a baker iii and soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze 
would enable soviet citizens for the first time to use rubles to buy 
tickets on us airlines 
that will open up travel to many soviet citizens who do not have 
access to us dollars or other easilyconvertible currencies with 
which to purchase tickets the soviet ruble generally cannot be 
exchanged for other forms of currency 
under the agreement soviet airlines would serve as a middleman 
in selling such tickets to soviet travelers the pact calls for up 
to 875 percent of tickets on any given flight to be made available 
to purchasers with rubles 
the pact would increase from the current four to 14 us and 
soviet cities served now flights are allowed only between moscow 
leningrad washington and new york 
total passenger and cargo flights per side will increase from 
under eight at present to 15 immediately to 42 by next april and to 
58 by april 1992 
an ocean studies agreement also to be signed by baker and 
shevardnadze calls for shared use of research vessels and a broad 
range of oceanographic research cooperation according to a white 
house fact sheet 
a moremodest ussoviet joint effort to explore the oceans was 
suspended by the united states with the 1979 soviet invasion of 
afghanistan 
another agreement to be signed by shevardnadze and us 
transportation scretary samuel skinner seeks to put ussoviet 
maritime relations on a more normal footing including increased 
access to each others ports 
agreements will also be signed by other administration officials 
and shevardnadze on cultural centers customs cooperation and 
distribution of the magazines intended for each others country 
fitzwater said 
</TEXT>
