the soviet union has protested illegal japanese 
fishing in its waters and is seeking millions of dollars in 
compensation for losses an official said thursday 
the foreign ministry delivered a protest note to the japanese 
embassy in moscow complaining of systematic violations of fishing 
treaties to the point that the agreements themselves are 
threatened spokesman vadim p perfiliev said 
perfiliev told reporters that illegal fishing exhausts stock 
reserves costing the soviet union millions of dollars he said the 
illegal fishing must be stopped and the damages paid 
in tokyo soviet diplomatic sources said a protest was addressed 
to north korea as well concerning the illegal salmon fishing in 
sovietclaimed waters of the north pacific 
it referred to the seizure of six japanese fishing boats may 913 
off sovietheld sakhalin island said the diplomats who spoke on 
condition of anonymity the boats and their crews were released soon 
after the seizures 
perfiliev said the actions of the japanese side were to blame 
for the incidents its obvious that if not for such crude 
violations the soviet side would not have seen the necessity of 
acting to correct the situation 
the protest lodged with japan did not however mention the 
highly publicized seizures may 1922 of 10 north korean vessels 
manned mostly by japanese fishermen that were also found operating 
illegally in soviet waters 
moscow has filed a separate complaint with the north korean 
embassy over those seizures the diplomatic sources said 
i believe this is the most largescale case to date one 
source said they were caught with 170000 salmon on board thats 
quite a lot 
although 70 percent to 80 percent of the crew members and much of 
the equipment aboard the vessels were japanese the sources said 
the soviet union believes legal responsibility remains with north 
korea because the ships flew the north korean flag and had north 
korean captains 
the japanese foreign ministry on thursday announced that 169 
japanese fishermen were being held by the soviets on shikotan a 
small island in the kurile chain just off the northern japanese 
island of hokkaido 
the soviet sources could not confirm the number of japanese 
fishermen being detained 
the japanese fishermen are believed to have thought they would be 
