<TEXT>
the narrow hot smoky corridors of a 
resettlement office are crammed with soviet jews young and 
middleaged couples elderly women world war ii veterans with rows 
of medals on their chests 
hysterical arguments flare up in the long lines besieged 
officials look exhausted a woman tries to push ahead of others to 
a lawyer who is supposed to help immigrants deal with landlords 
several people shout angrily finally someone cries please 
please stop it are we all animals 
confusion is everywhere as israel struggles to absorb a huge 
influx of soviet jews that caught the government by surprise 
threatening to overwhelm social services and balloon the national 
debt and unemployment 
the surge of arrivals also complicates the middle east 
situation artab nations see the immigration as a threat to 
palestinians in the occupied west bank and gaza strip 
officials and private citizens in israel welcome the newcomers 
whatever the problems they pose as a fulfillment of the ageold 
dream of ingathering jewish exiles 
israelis hope the tide will result in the country having enough 
jews to survive economically and militarily to keep abreast of an 
arab population with a much higher birth rate 
the soviet immigants also may break the deadlock in the struggle 
for political control between the centerleft labor party of shimon 
peres and the rightwing likud bloc led by yitzhak shamir the 
caretaker prime minister 
they will tip the ethnic balance between the jews of european 
origin and those from middle east countries how virtually equal in 
number and influence the relative weight given to religious and 
secular issues 
already their presence has changed the face of israeli society 
television news carries subtitles in the cyrillic alphabet 
banks advertise savings plans in russian 
department store chains hire russianspeaking personnel and 
offer the newcomers special installment plans liquor stores stock 
israelimade vodka called by such familiar names as stolichnaya and 
zubrowka a polish brand popular in the soviet union 
satellite dishes on immigrants houses are tuned to moscow 
television newspaper stands offer russianlanguage weeklies 
british tycoon robert maxwell and the hebrew newspaper maariv plan 
to publish a daily in russian 
state television has devoted hours of programming to the new 
israelis including a threehour broadcast with live hookups to 
moscow and a to plane carrying immigrants from from budapest 
hungary 
pushed by growing uncertainty and antisemitism in the soviet 
union and new restrictions on us immigration soviet arrivals 
rose from a trickle to a record 35000 so far in 1990 
forecasts say 500000 to 1 million soviet jews could come 
eventually that would be the largest influx since 19481951 when 
the new nation took in 685000 immigrants from 42 countries 
doubling its population 
months passed before israeli officials fully comprehended the 
sheer volume which has reached 1000 on some days 
the official forecast of 40000 immigrants in 1990 has been 
raised to at least 100000 and possibly 150000 
israel is now in the midst of an emergency said yitzhak 
peretz the absorption minister the wave of immigration grows 
every day we must act urgently 
jews abroad have undertaken a major fundraising effort 
including a pledge of 420 million by us jews but it is far from 
enough 
in early may the government added 125 billion to the 900 
million budgeted for settling immigrants that meant budget cuts 
and more borrowing abroad 
the system cant keep up 
in holon a tel aviv suburb nissim spiegelmacher gets up at 4 
am an hour later he joins a line forming outside the absorption 
ministry office which opens at 7 am other immigrants who 
arrive later are turned away 
an official has to deal with 35 families a day said 
spiegelmacher 49 a bearded engineer from odessa the rooms are 
crowded the organization is terrible 
his wife nora a 47yearold chemist complained that 
government offices were open only in the morning while they were 
in hebrew class one of them has to miss class in order to get the 
paperwork done she said 
alexei streimushov a theater director from kiev in his late 
20s mused that long lines were familiar to soviet immigrants 
in those lines people bark at each other they start to hate 
each other just like in the soviet union he said 
housing and employment are the main problems the government 
wants to start building 70000 apartments this year including 
45000 public housing units but officials say the first units 
would take 16 months to complete 
the government system of subsidizing rental apartments has 
pushed prices up and led to a projected shortage of 29000 units in 
the mediumprice range by the end of this year 
nathan sharansky who spent nine years in soviet prison camps 
for human rights activism and immigrated in 1986 said his warnings 
about an immigration boom had been ignored and he fears the housing 
crisis is not taken seriously 
we have lines of people seeking apartments and its already 
clear that we would not have a single apartment in a few months 
he said for a year we speak about construction and we are not 
building 
israels economy still staggers from loss of tourism and extra 
military costs resulting from the 2yearold palestinian uprising 
unemployment has averaged 93 percent so far this year 
finding jobs for the soviet jews is especially difficult because 
one in four is a highly educated professional they face tough 
competition in a labor market that already has 24 percent 
professionals compared to 16 percent in the united states 
david mena head of the staterun employment service said most 
immigrants would start hunting jobs late this summer when their 
hebrew language courses are completed 
when we have six people competing for every job and no new 
jobs being created these immigrants would not find jobs in their 
profession he said 
immigration has inflamed ethnic tensions among jews a debate on 
resettlement costs has pitted many ashkenazis of european descent 
including soviet jews against sephardis of middle eastern origin 
there are fears that financial resources are being diverted from 
the negev and other predominantly sephardi areas where factories 
have been closing and laying off workers 
some callers to radio shows and letters to newspapers have 
suggested the immigrants be put in tent camps like the sephardis 
were in the 1950s 
whether more of the newcomers will choose likud or labor is not 
known but most are secular and may upset the ultraorthodox 
political factions ability to be a kingmaker in coalition 
governments 
the interior ministry is controlled by the shas party which 
represents ultraorthodox sephardi jews it demanded proof that the 
immigrants were jewish 
this angered the soviet jews officials said many had mixed 
marriages and were even nonjews by orthodox definition 
the influx has stirred national pride israelis have volunteered 
to help adopting families and taking gifts of furniture and 
kitchen utensils to immigrant homes at least 50 volunteer groups 
have been formed 
in many places we have more volunteers ready to help the 
immigrants than we have immigrants said yuri stern an adviser 
to parliaments committee on absorption 
uri gordon head of the jewish agencys immigration department 
said israel needs 6 million jews to be secure enough to make peace 
with the arabs 
negotiations with our neighbors will then be easier he 
said every jew who comes from russia makes the prospects for 
peace stronger 
arabs especially the palestine liberation organization have 
expressed fear that immigrants will flood the occupied territories 
displacing palestinians 
israeli officials said only about 200 soviet jews had settled in 
the occupied lands 
