<TEXT>
rain has poured down all morning 
but as the trail dips into rain forest any thoughts of discomfort 
vanish amid the lush undergrowth 
there is almost a sense of entering a sanctuary as the damp 
ground cover muffles the thud of boots the only sounds are water 
dripping from the canopy of branches onto huge ferns the gurgle of 
a distant brook and the occasional trill or shriek of an unseen 
bird 
the fresh scent of rain mingles with the smells of the verdant 
forest 
sunlight begins to break through the lowhanging trees 
vibrantly highlighting every possible shade of green rocks and 
limbs are covered with moss so thick it seems possible to take a 
nap and wake up covered with it 
after a few hours the trail climbs above the tree line to 
reveal stunning views of deep blue lakes below and craggy mountains 
still covered with snow in late summer clouds begin to move back 
in obscuring the sheer cliffs of distant fjords in mist 
this is hiking in new zealand which attracts nature lovers from 
thousands of miles away even the main industries help create an 
idyllic landscape rolling green hills of rich farmland and pasture 
dotted with millions of sheep 
hiking and bicycling seem a way of life for the hardy residents 
who protect and enjoy their environment they have built thousands 
of miles of hiking trails that are virtually free of debris 
in most places the water remains clean enough to drink from the 
streams at night the sky is so clear the bright stars barely 
twinkle only a sliver of moon is needed to see clearly without a 
flashlight 
for those tired of carrying and pitching tents many trails have 
the added advantage of communal wooden huts that provide warmth and 
shelter they also offer a welcome bit of camaraderie for people of 
various nationalities who range from couples carrying infants to 
people in their early 70s 
a few huts are near hot springs where a long soak can ease the 
aches of a days hiking shelters on the most popular trails fill 
quickly especially in peak seasons so early arrivals get the 
bunks and latecomers sleep on the floor 
its lovely to fall asleep with rain drumming on the roof but 
there are some inherent problems with communal living not the 
least of them are people who snore and others who like late parties 
many of the trails known here as tracks are far from easy new 
zealanders dont seem fond of switchbacks preferring instead to 
challenge their legs and lungs with more direct routes up and down 
the rough terrain 
one particularly tough track rises to a ridge 3569 feet above 
the valley in a series of steps carved from the hillside through a 
boulder field and over an anklewrenching stretch of loose rock 
called scree 
whatever the difficulties theres nothing like the isolation of 
hiking down a mountain as the early morning fog rises blanketing 
everything in a shroud of white only the sound of your footsteps 
and the trickle of distant glacierfed waterfalls break the 
silence 
it is like visiting an alien planet to trek across the desolate 
crater of an inactive volcano where lakes of startling green 
contrast with gray volcanic dust 
new zealand offers numerous coves and rushing rivers that are 
ideal for canoeing or whitewater rafting there are streems and 
lakes rich in trout black sand beaches for those who want a rest 
wildlife includes albatrosses with 10foot wingspans colonies 
of seals and penguins mischievous mountain parrots called keas and 
the reticent flightless kiwi bird that has become the national 
symbol 
the weather often consists of surprises and good rain gear is a 
must forecasting seems more guesswork than science particularly 
on the south islands west coast where rainfall may reach 300 
inches a year 
sunshine turns quickly to brooding clouds which spew downpours 
and give way to sun again trails can change to small streams dirt 
to mud solid footholds to slick rock and roots 
sandflies are probably the worst curse of hiking in new zealand 
the tiny insects swarm and bite sometimes drawing blood 
they move slowly however which means a good walking pace can 
leave them behind repellants generally drive them off and they 
disappear at night 
keas found in higher elevations are covered with thick green 
feathers that often reveal an undercovering of red while in flight 
sometimes they take hikers by surprise with low passes and loud 
screeches 
if humans give them food they dont have to spend all day 
hunting it which leaves time for mischief that sometimes borders 
on the malicious 
they have been known to tear up boots backpacks and bicycle 
seats with their sharp powerful beaks a traveler told of two keas 
that cooperated in an attempt to fly off with his bicycle helmet 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

