<TEXT>
the eroded soil swirling in the smoky hill 
river after a hard rain is the legacy of sodbusting pioneers and 
more than a century of poor farming practices 
the smoky hill and other rivers look like a spilled cup of 
heavily creamed coffee because they carry a muddy mix of water 
rich top soil and farm chemical residues 
ecologist wes jackson blames exploitative agriculture 
farming that relies on working the ground with heavy equipment and 
tons of chemicals to fertilize crops and protect them from weeds 
and pests 
mining the soil he said describing modern agriculture as a 
carryover from the days when people farmed a patch of ground until 
it was unproductive and then moved on 
and agricultural chemicals he said are substances with which 
our tissues have had no experience 
at 53 jackson founder of the land institute has held to his 
ideas long enough that admiration has replaced ridicule he has 
gone from the target of mocking barbs to a respected leader in the 
sustainable agriculture movement which seeks to reduce or 
eliminate the use of chemicals and and change other consumptive 
farming practices 
the message from jackson has been much the same as it has been 
for 20 years but the world around him has evolved and he now sits 
on a us department of agriculture panel evaluating proposals for 
low input sustainable agriculture or lisa research projects 
he addressed an earth day crowd of 100000 people at lincoln 
park in chicago 
george ham a kansas state university associate dean of 
agriculture and former head of ksus agronomy department has a 
cordial relationship with jackson they disagree on the definition 
of sustainable agriculture and other points 
i certainly recognize his professional background and 
expertise and certainly recognize where hes coming from ham 
said in terms of our approaches to sustainability ours is short 
term while his is more long term 
for instance kansas state is helping farmers gradually decrease 
the amount they plow and the quantities of chemicals they use 
jackson however looks to the day when the plowing and chemical 
use would be for the most part eliminated 
ham agreed that agriculture has evolved and environmental 
concerns now are more important kansas state is placing new 
emphasis on looking at water quality and how chemicals move through 
the soil he said 
an increasing number of people are finally recognizing that 
agriculture itself is an ecological problem outranking industrial 
pollution jackson said 
a lot of the resistance to my ideas came from my wellknown 
stands on the vietnam war civil rights and the environment 
jackson said people thought i was some kind of nut 
even his wife dana concedes he is outlandish she says thats 
why he is a soughtafter speaker 
and how receptive could farmers and agricultural academicians be 
when a speaker refers to farming as the barbaric plunder of 
nature and compares chemical treatment of soils and crops as 
fossilfuel chemotherapy 
jackson has chided farmers for wearing caps with seed and 
chemical company logos advertising the corporate agribusiness 
lords for whom they work 
and he said helping farmers cope daytoday is like caring for a 
cancer patient this is noble work but it is more for the 
purpose of helping someone cope than it is to change the patients 
fate he said 
jackson who has a bachelors degree in biology a masters 
degree in botany and a doctorate in genetics has been a teacher 
and lecturer for nearly three decades 
he doesnt pretend to have answers for all the questions he 
asks he doesnt suggest farmers immediately abandon all chemicals 
and tilling he believes a radical political agenda and an as yet 
undiscovered economy are needed to reform agriculture 
the land institute which jackson and his wife founded in 1976 
uses the prairie as its standard for a new agriculture 
supported by foundations and a corps of individual donors the 
nonprofit institute employs 13 people and has 10 interns each year 
for a 43week term of study the interns receive 125 a month 
preference is given to people who plan to earn graduate degrees and 
work in the field of sustainable agriculture 
most of the work is targeted at developing a domestic prairie 
in technical terms jackson calls it a herbaceous perennial 
seedproducing polyculture that wouldnt require fertilizer 
pesticides or herbicides the legumes and seedbearing grasses 
grown for human and animal food wouldnt need annual plowing 
several plants show promise they are eastern gamma grass a 
highprotein warm season grass related to corn leymus a cool 
season wild rye and illinois bundle flower a native prairie 
legume 
researchers also are working with a grain sorghumjohnson grass 
crossbreed they hope to wed the domestic milo plants grain 
production with the noxious weeds perennial and winter hardiness 
traits 
of the institutes 278 acres 90 are native prairie and 50 are 
replanted prairie there are also a herbery where more than 300 
wild plants were transplanted for study a 140foot greenhouse and 
various test plots 
a brick 1960sera splitlevel rural home serves as 
administrative and research offices the jacksons live in the small 
home they built nearby in 1971 
as the institute has grown its budget has climbed from 16000 
a year to nearly 500000 
the time frame for results from work at the land as its backers 
call it is 25 50 or 100 years even then the effort might not 
reach its goals 
but he is resolute about his calling 
lets find out from the ecology what it is about natures 
community that sees to it all the ecological bills get paid he 
said what other choice do we have 
</TEXT>
