<TEXT>
the us steel industrys recovery from a severe 
downturn in the early 1980s could be harmed by cleanair controls 
under consideration by congress executives of major steel 
companies said at their annual convention 
reining in proposed pollution regulation has become a major 
policy issue for the industry said thomas c graham president of 
uss the steelmaking division of usx corp 
other issues of concern include the high cost of capital in the 
united states and foreign competition executives said wednesday at 
the american iron and steel institute gathering 
clearly the environment is again the major public policy 
issue facing steel producers after a decade in which trade was at 
center stage said graham who called some cleanair proposals 
being considered by congress draconian 
he said the steel industry is willing to spend more to install 
pollutioncontrol equipment but only if the results justify the 
costs 
we oppose requirements which would drain our available capital 
and which would cause plant closings and substantial job losses 
without verifiable scientific indication of real benefit to the 
environment or improvement to public health he told industry 
executives and reporters 
graham who heads the nations largest steelmaker said steel 
producers spent 7 billion over the last three decades to eliminate 
90 percent to 95 percent of the pollutants they put into the air 
and water 
the industrys main concern in the current debate is provisions 
of the senate cleanair bill that would force automatic shutdowns 
of plants that produce coke a key ingredient in steelmaking 
unless they meet certain pollution standards graham said 
he called a provision that would give steel companies up to 30 
years to comply with the coke oven standards misleading 
the fact is that the mere passage of the shutdown provisions 
would have an immediate chilling impact he said how could we 
justify making the major investments needed in the next five to 10 
years to rebuild aging coke batteries if they face mandatory 
shutdown in the future 
foreign steelmakers who are not facing the kind of 
environmental cost burdens we are would love to see passage of 
the senate shutdown provisions graham said 
the executives said research continues into direct steelmaking 
in which iron ore would be melted directly eliminating the need 
for coke but that the technology was at least 10 years away 
the chairman of the trade association frank w luerssen called 
the cost of capital the domestic steel industrys top concern 
without access to lowercost borrowing us steel companies 
cannot compete with foreign makers in modernizing plants said 
luerssen who is chairman and chief executive officer of inland 
steel industries inc 
he said companies in western europe and japan can borrow money 
at lower interest rates a major factor in the decision by many 
us steel companies to enter joint ventures with foreign companies 
and in foreign purchases of us steel plants 
the profitability of steel companies is occasionally too low 
to attract lowcost capital said joseph f toot jr president 
of steel products maker timken co on the other hand 
profitability can be substantially improved through investment in 
worldleading technology 
commenting on japanese investment in us steelmaking in recent 
years he said it is intriguing to observe that the japanese 
investor can apparently see through this catch22 and see that in 
the long haul the american steel industry will become more 
profitable 
on another topic industry leaders said they support the bush 
administrations efforts to eliminate dumping of foreign steel in 
the united states and subsidies from foreign governments to their 
steelmakers 
the current limits on steel imports are scheduled to expire in 
march 1992 by then the administration hopes to have eliminated 
subsidies and dumping or selling foreign steel in the united 
states at below the cost of production 
graham said the industry would seek no further protection or 
extension of the import limits if dumping and subsidies were 
eliminated 
he also said the industry believes the main reason it wasnt 
competitive globally several years ago was a grossly overvalued 
dollar rather than just unfair foreign competition a stronger 
dollar makes us exports more costly in terms of foreign 
currencies 
he said the federal reserves move to ease inflation in the 
early 1980s by raising interest rates thus increasing the value of 
the dollar helped almost destroy american manufacturing 
competitiveness 
