<TEXT>
a new delaware law that allows banks with 
operations in the state to sell and underwrite insurance nationwide 
was only hours old when the insurance industry challenged it 
gov michael n castle signed the legislation into law wednesday 
and it took effect immediately 
two hours later a petition was filed with the federal reserve 
board to block citicorp the nations largest banking company from 
taking advantage of the law citicorp plans to locate an insurance 
headquarters in dover and sell insurance nationwide through a 
subsidiary of its delaware bank 
the petition filed by five national insurance agent 
associations and three local groups alleges citicorp is attempting 
to evade the federal bank holding company act which prohibits bank 
holding companies and their subsidiaries from selling insurance 
said william r anderson associate general counsel of the national 
association of life underwriters in washington 
citicorp officials who had not seen the petition were expected 
to respond today said david swayze a wilmington attorney and 
citicorp lobbyist 
the law is a continuation of delawares effort to stay in the 
forefront of an everchanging financial services industry 
in 1981 the state enacted the financial center development act 
which offered tax incentives and eliminated interest rate ceilings 
to lure outofstate banks to move their credit card operations to 
delaware delaware was the first to relax its banking laws and 
other states soon followed suit 
since 1981 the state enacted about eight laws aimed at making 
it more attractive for financial service companies to locate in 
delaware and castle said the trend would continue 
we cannot rest on our laurels its not just banking but all 
financial services that interest us here in delaware and were 
always looking at ways to improve our business environment to be 
ahead of the curve to be ahead of our competitors to be ahead of 
everybody else in the country castle said 
secretary of state michael harkins said there is a possibility 
that with the new law a major european bank could open a 
subsidiary in delaware he would not identify the bank he said 
however that delaware wants to bring in foreign banks 
in addition to banking reforms delaware is known worldwide for 
its favorable incorporation laws more than half of the nations 
fortune 500 companies are incorporated in the state 
as he signed the bill wednesday castle said it was possible the 
new law would be challenged by insurance companies or other states 
but he predicted such challenges would fail 
the law allows banks chartered in delaware after 1934 to sell 
and underwrite insurance nationwide most banks chartered before 
1934 already have such powers those chartered earlier that do not 
have such powers must obtain permission from the state legislature 
a companion bill also signed into law restricts the types of 
insurance banks can sell within the state but allows them to sell 
a full range of products outside delaware 
the banks must locate their insurance headquarters in delaware 
to take advantage of the laws 
chase manhattan corp the nations no 2 bank also has said it 
plans to sell insurance through its office in the state 
more than half of the states allow banks to engage in some form 
of insurance sales but they limit the sales to within state 
boundaries said maryliz meany spokeswoman for the american 
bankers association in washington the banking industry considers 
the new law a boon for consumers because it expands the market 
theres been a sense that if the insurance industry allowed 
more players in the market the price will come down meany said 
she said the law gives insurance powers to about 40 financial 
institutions nationwide that have affiliates in delaware 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

