a fouryear effort to revamp the world trading 
system remained in doubt after us and european negotiators failed 
to budge from their positions on government payments to farmers 
no headway in resolving the stubborn dispute was reported 
wednesday after lengthy discussions by key trade officials of the 
united states and the european community 
we have hit a snag said us trade representative carla 
hills 
mrs hills and other american officials tried to use a meeting 
of the 24nation organization for economic cooperation and 
development to advance the uruguay round of trade talks but their 
efforts were blunted by the community made up of a dozen west 
european nations 
this is not a negotiating forum said frans andriessen the 
communitys trading chief 
the americans want the europeans to agree to do more to slash 
their costly subsidies to farmers but the europeans so far have 
refused 
the dispute has stalled the uruguay round negotiations an 
ambitious effort to overhaul the world trading system by reducing 
trade barriers in 15 areas including agriculture and textiles 
the bargaining among nearly 100 nations began in uruguay in 1986 
and is scheduled to end with a final round of talks in december 
but the latest failure to find common ground on farm subsidies 
does not bode well the talks are held under the auspices of the 
general agreement on tariffs and trade a forum and an agreement 
for promoting freer trade 
canadas international trade minister john crosbie was glum 
when he came out of wednesdays discussions 
it was discouraging he said both sides he said seemed 
to be so adamant of their own positions 
andriessen acknowledged that the inability of the community to 
change its position might be viewed negatively but he predicted 
the trading partners would be able to come to a satisfactory 
agreement 
mrs hills said the negotiators would be in grave difficulty 
if they were unable to settle the farm subsidy dispute by december 
the united states has linked agreement on the agriculture issue to 
success in other areas as well but andriessen noted that 
agriculture is not the only issue since the talks cover 14 
other areas 
american officials wanted thursdays final statement at the oecd 
meeting to show that both sides were willing to lower trade 
barriers so that farm exports would have better access to other 
countries local markets 
they also wanted the community to promise to reduce farm 
payments that encourage overproduction of crops and to slash 
subsidies that help farmers sell their goods on foreign markets 
the united states complains that export subsidies have helped the 
community increase its share of the world market 
the community refused to pledge to widen its markets to foreign 
food products or to curb export subsidies according to us 
officials 
