<TEXT>
a tentative deal reached by northwest 
airlines honeywell inc and the soviet union could relieve 
overseas air routes and make groundbased navigation equipment 
obsolete officials from the two companies say 
it will allow us to put more airplanes in the sky more 
safely bob buley manager of flight standards and product 
development for northwest said wednesday 
we think it could be the sole source of navigation by 1995 
said jim koch vice president of minneapolis operations for 
honeywell 
the joint venture allows for the simultaneous testing of soviet 
and us satellites as a navigation guide for commercial jets it 
was announced at a news conference by honeywell chairman and chief 
executive officer james renier and northwest chairman alfred 
checchi 
the executives said the agreement signed by honeywell northwest 
and the soviet union is subject to government approval in both 
countries 
under the agreement the soviets would deliver equipment to 
honeywell and northwest late this year the exchange would enable 
honeywell to build units capable of reading commercial aviation 
signals from the soviet glosnass satellite system military 
aviation signals would not be accessible koch said 
the equipment would be mounted on a northwest 747 cargo plane 
for test flying through september 1991 the same plane in april 
began testing honeywell equipment that reads commercial navigation 
signals from the us global positioning system of satellites 
the 21 active satellites planned for each system could enable 
pilots to doublecheck the positions of their planes to guard 
against inaccurate readings buley said the system also could 
enable planes to land at airports that lack sophisticated 
groundbased navigation equipment he said 
it will literally open up the globe to commercial aviation 
buley said 
koch said northwest and honeywell will strive to have the dual 
satellite navigation system certified for use in all commercial 
jetliners by 1993 they will seek certification for the system as a 
planes sole source of navigation by 1995 
transoceanic air travel would benefit the most by the advance 
buley said the absence of groundbased navigation during overseas 
flights requires pilots to approximate their whereabouts and keep 
about a 60mile buffer between planes he said 
satellite navigation would allow pilots to nearly pinpoint their 
whereabouts and fly within five or even three miles of other 
planes he said todays reference systems for flying overseas can 
result in position errors of about 10 nautical miles for every five 
hours of flying honeywell said in a news release 
were running into gridlock over there now buley said of 
routes from the united states to the pacific rim where northwest 
is dominant were having to take delays getting off the ground 
because we have to wait for the planes ahead of us to get well into 
the system 
the agreement would not give honeywell exclusive rights to 
develop equipment capable of reading soviet satellite signals but 
it would give the controls maker a head start on a potentially huge 
market koch said 
koch said the soviets alone have up to 4000 commercial 
airplanes excluding the soviet union the worldwide fleet of 
commercial aircraft is estimated at about 9100 said tom cole a 
spokesman for the aircraft maker boeing co of seattle 
buley said it could cost between 25000 and 50000 to equip 
each plane with equipment needed to receive satellite signals the 
sales would be made by honeywells space and aviation division 
which accounted for about 2 billion of the companys 61 billion 
in sales last year 
checchi said northwest would eventually like to extend its 
routes to eastern europe and the soviet union but he said such an 
expansion is not our highest priority 
