<TEXT>
the belzberg family of canada has 
abandoned its bid to acquire armstrong world industries ending a 
feud that prompted the enactment of the nations toughest 
antitakeover law 
first city capital corp a belzberg entity said wednesday it 
had sold its 48 million shares in armstrong a flooringproducts 
and furnishings manufacturer with 25 billion in annual gross 
revenues 
armstrong purchased 37 million of the shares and its board had 
authorized the repurchase of up to 4 million shares said company 
spokesman john scheldrup he said the shares were bought at 3575 
per share 
the move comes about a month after the belzbergs failed to seat 
three of four nominees on the armstrong board and the state enacted 
legislation that requires corporate raiders to surrender shortterm 
profits from thwarted takeover bids 
first city spokeswoman dezanne philips acknowledged the 
stringent takeover law and the largely unsuccessful proxy fight 
played a role in the decision 
the antitakeover legislation was drafted last year after the 
belzbergs first disclosed an interest in acquiring the company its 
introduction triggered a nationwide debate between investor groups 
and state labor and business interests 
the belzbergs mounted an aggressive lobbying effort to defeat 
the bill in the pennsylvania legislature claiming it would protect 
ineffective management and strip stockholders of traditional 
rights but the bill was approved by wide margins 
in addition to garnishing profits in failed takeover bids the 
law also restricts the voting rights of raiders and preserves labor 
contracts when corporations change hands 
