<TEXT>
american demands that the european community slash 
its export subsidies to farmers would be politically impossible 
to meet a trade bloc official said thursday 
but other officials warned that the communitys refusal to budge 
was threatening the outcome of ambitious plans to overhaul the world 
trading system 
us treasury secretary nicholas brady said the fight over 
subsidies that broke out at the annual meeting of the organization 
for economic cooperation and development was a disagreement that 
was waiting to happen 
but brady told a breakfast meeting of reporters it is best 
that we face the differences in the free world openly and with some 
energy now rather than wait until the last minute 
at issue is an american demand that the 12nation european 
community do much more to slash its costly subsidies to farmers 
which the united states claims hinder trade the europeans so far 
have refused 
ray macsharry the communitys agriculture chief said the 
trading bloc could not eliminate its export subsidy program 
that is politically impossible and will not happen he said 
were best to get involved in serious negotiations about making 
progress for greater liberalization of trade 
he said eliminating the subsidies would mean higher farm prices 
in europe and unemployment for millions of farmers the community 
gives exporters help so more expensive european farm products can 
compete with lower prices on the world market 
the deadlock has stalled the uruguay round negotiations a 
fouryear effort to overhaul the world trading system 
australian foreign affairs minister gareth evans said the 
european position was simply not a tenable longterm position 
they will be putting at risk not just agriculture but the whole 
round of trade negotiations if they stick to a position as tight 
as that he said 
the talks involving some 100 nations are designed to reduce 
barriers to trade in 15 areas including agriculture and textiles 
the bargaining opened in 1986 and is due to end in december it 
is being held under the auspices of the general agreement on tariffs 
and trade a forum and agreement for promoting freer trade 
trade and finance officials of 24 industrialized nations ended 
the oecd meeting by agreeing to take urgent steps to reform 
agricultural policy as regards support and protection so as to 
permit greater liberalization of trade 
but their final statement reflected the differences between the 
united states and the community over how to do that 
the statement said some nations wanted the others to pledge to 
make changes in the areas of internal support barriers to market 
access and export subsidies us officials had pressed for that 
wording 
in addition to resisting elimination of export subsidies the 
common market has refused the us demands that it open its markets 
wider to foreign farm products and cut farm payments that encourage 
crop surpluses 
the ec has urged a more general approach such as finding a way 
to measure a countrys trade performance in agriculture and then 
work to reduce that level 
the united states and other countries have insisted the farm 
issue is crucial to a successful outcome of the overall trade talks 
in their final statement the ministers promised to make every 
effort to overcome the differences by a july 23 negotiating 
session in geneva by then the united states wants preliminary 
agreements or negotiating texts in all 15 areas under discussion 
oecd members are australia austria belgium britain canada 
denmark finland france greece iceland ireland italy japan 
luxembourg the netherlands new zealand norway portugal spain 
sweden switzerland turkey the united states and west germany 
