<TEXT>
a pennsylvania state court ruling barring a phone 
company from installing devices that alert customers to the numbers 
of incoming calls could provide ammunition to those trying to block 
the service elsewhere 
the caller id service has been criticized as an invasion of 
privacy by foes but praised by supporters as a way to detect 
unwanted calls and speed the jobs of emergency workers 
pennsylvanias commonwealth court ruled wednesday that bell of 
pennsylvania may not offer the service on the grounds that it is an 
invasion of privacy and violates state laws on wiretapping and 
phonenumber tracing 
bell of pennsylvania said it might appeal to the state supreme 
court 
janlori goldman an attorney with the american civil liberties 
union said the decision changes the nature of the debate over 
caller id 
most groups with concerns about the service such as the aclu 
have said they will not oppose it if the phone companies provide a 
way for customers to block their numbers from appearing on caller id 
screens when they place calls 
but the pennsylvania court went beyond such concerns in finding 
that caller id as a concept violates state laws with or without the 
numberblocking devices 
ms goldman said the ruling by implication could mean caller id 
services are illegal in other states that have similar wiretap and 
numbertracing laws 
she said the aclu is pressing for congress to enact federal 
legislation regulating caller id services bills to do so are 
pending in the house and senate 
bell of pennsylvania does not plan to provide blocking devices 
for most customers including those with unlisted numbers such 
devices only would be provided to domestic violence shelters and law 
enforcement agencies 
the phone company argues that blocking devices would negate the 
usefulness of the service by allowing those who abuse the phone 
system such as obscene callers to elude detection 
rochelle dreyfuss a law professor at new york university and an 
expert on privacy law said the pennsylvania decision could be used 
to bolster lawsuits in other states seeking to block or modify 
caller id services 
its common for lawyers to argue that this is what other 
states have done with this issue she said 
edward martone executive director of the aclus new jersey 
chapter said the pennsylvania decision helps us with our 
arguments here 
the new jersey aclu opposed the caller id service that has been 
offered by new jersey bell since late 1988 both the new jersey and 
pennsylvania phone companies are part of philadelphiabased bell 
atlantic corp 
the aclu has no active case against the state or the phone 
company seeking to block the service but martone said it was 
considering several options to return the issue to public discussion 
the office of the new jersey public advocate which represents 
consumer interests before state bodies also opposed caller id in 
hearings before state regulatory agencies 
the office said it believed the service was a privacy invasion 
and that it could harm hotlines and similar services that offer 
anonymous advice said robin portnoi the assistant deputy public 
advocate 
new jersey bell which offers no blocking devices to any 
customer has addressed the concerns of law enforcement agencies 
and social service groups such as shelters by offering them outgoing 
phone lines only ms portnoi said 
shelters fear battered women would be afraid to call their 
spouses if it would lead to alerting the husbands to their location 
when a person called by a shelter or law enforcement agency tries 
to return the call by using the number that flashed on his caller id 
screen he either gets a recording saying the number does not accept 
incoming calls or is transferred to an answering service under 
several options provided by new jersey bell said spokesman peter 
ventimiglia 
however ms portnoi said the state public advocate has asked 
us in light of the pennsylvania decision to take another look at 
caller id in new jersey 
concern over privacy issues sparked california lawmakers to ban 
the service unless the phone company offers a blocking device new 
york regulators took a similar stance when they approved caller id 
on a trial basis in the rochester area 
caller id is already available or is about to be introduced in 
other states including maryland virginia tennessee and west 
virginia 
</TEXT>
