<TEXT>
federal securities regulators voted thursday to 
explore rules changes that could allow us investors to participate 
in tender offers by foreign companies 
the securities and exchange commission voted unanimously to seek 
public comment on the appropriateness of permitting selected foreign 
tender offers to proceed in this country under foreign rules and 
regulations 
such an exception to sec rules is still a long way off but the 
commission took the first step toward even considering it 
currently those buying and selling publiclyoffered securities 
in this country must comply with sec regulations which some 
foreign concerns find too expensive or too onerous 
consequently rather than cut in us holders of foreign stocks 
on tender offers for their securities overseas concerns have chosen 
to exclude them 
the sec will issue what they call a concept release seeking 
public opinion on the idea of allowing foreign rules to apply where 
the us securities holdings involved constitute a relatively small 
portion of the securities in the transaction 
among the things that have yet to be decided the definition of a 
relatively small portion 
